INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (122, 1, '2013-09-05 23:04:22', '2013-09-05 23:04:22', '<div>

<b>HISTORY</b>

</div>
Gordon College, also known as Dalubhasaang Gordon in Filipino, is a local government-funded college in Olongapo City, Philippines. It was founded on February 24, 1999 by virtue of City Ordinance No. 9, and is composed of four constituent colleges: College of Computer Studies, College of Business and Accountancy, College of Education, and College of Nursing. Other academic units include the School of Midwifery, Department of Vocational Technology, Faculty of Arts and Sciences, Center for Research and Development, and Institute of Graduate Studies.
<div>

<b>VISION</b>

</div>
A premiere institution of higher learning committed to the holistic development of the human person and the society.
<div>

<b>MISSION</b>

</div>
To produce well-trained, skilled, dynamic and competitive individuals imbued with values and attitudes and responsive to the changing needs of the local, national and global communities.
<div>

<b>GOALS</b>

</div>
The Gordon College shall:

1. Provide opportunities that will enable individuals to acquire a high level of professional, technical and vocational courses of studies.

2. Develop innovative programs, projects and models of practice by undertaking research and studies.

3. Promote community development through relevant extension programs.

4. Provide opportunities for entrepreneurship and employability of graduates.
<div>
<b><strong>GC-CCS ACHIEVEMENTS</strong></b>
</div>
<ul>
	<li>First in Asia Pacific Region to roll-out the BlackBerry Academic Program</li>
	<li>Accredited Level 1 in IT Programs</li>
	<li>First in the Region who use Google University</li>
	<li>First in the Region who has a Web portal</li>
	<li>First in the Region who has a Mobile Portal</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;
<div>
<b><strong>STUDENTS and TEACHERS ACHIEVEMENTS</strong></b>
</div>
<ul>
	<li>3rd Place in IdeaSpace Bootcamp at Central Luzon</li>
	<li>Five Students who passed the International Certification Exam issued by IBM</li>
	<li>Joined the Startup Weekend Manila</li>
	<li>Joined the BB JamHack Asia in Hongkong</li>
	<li>Joined the BB JamHack Asia in Thailand</li>
	<li>Won Ms. SSITE 2011</li>
	<li>Won Mr. SSITE 2011</li>
	<li>Won Ms. SSITE 2013</li>
	<li>Won Mr. SSITE 2013 2nd Runner Up</li>
</ul>
<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">STUDENT INTERNSHIP PROGRAM</span></b>
<div>

<b>INTRODUCTION</b>

</div>
Practicum and/or On-the-job-training (OJT), often referred to as the cooperative method of instruction, provides an opportunity for students to gain meaningful paid or unpaid supervised work-based learning experiences in a business or industry setting. The OJT program/course is most often used to supplement classroom instruction in a specific career and technical education program, in order to give students the chance to apply the knowledge and skills acquired in school in a job that correlates to their instructional program.

Colleges and universities seek opportunities for their students to become involved in â€œreal worldâ€ activities or work assignments that will introduce them to and provide practical experiences in their chosen profession. This involvement may take the form of an internship requirement. In other situations, the opportunities may come in the form of a â€œpracticumâ€ in which students are assigned to work â€œin the fieldâ€ (for example, in a government agency or industry) to see firsthand how problems are addressed by professional in their chosen field.

The student intern is under the day-to-day direction of the sponsoring organization, may be given specific work assignments, and may work side-by-side with regular employees of the organization. A faculty member, in turn, provide the â€œbridgeâ€ between the work experience and the learning experienceâ€”giving guidance to the student and striving to place the field work into the broader context of the studentâ€™s educational program.

The practicum manual is intended to be a source of information and guidance for ITE students in practicum placement. Practicum provides students applied opportunity to develop and enhance their knowledge and skills, as well as increasing understanding and appreciation of a scientific and analytic approach to knowledge building and practice.

As mentioned in CHED CMO No. 53, S.2006, Internship/OJT/Practicum is an immersion program wherein the students will have the chance and opportunity to be with the IT industry. This program is important because the students will have the chance to apply the skills, knowledge and attitude learned in the school and at the same time the opportunity to experience the corporate environment. Learning expectations in the IT related field should be established between the HEI and the industry in the form of a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) or Memorandum of Understanding (MOU).

Internship is a requirement for the BSIT and BSIS program but optional for the BSCS program. Students are eligible to enroll the internship program after completing the 80% of the total number of units in the curriculum. The minimum number of internship hours for the BSIT and BSIS programs are 486 and 162 for the BSCS program.

<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Â </span></b>
<div>
<b><strong>POLICIES AND GUIDELINES FOR BSIT, BSIS, BSCS AND ACT PRACTICUM/ On-the-job Training (OJT)</strong></b>
<b><strong>General Objectives:</strong></b>
</div>
In response to meet the industryâ€™s demand for technically competent and well-rounded IT graduates, the practicum/OJT program aims to:
<ol start="1">
	<li>Provide the students an opportunity to be exposed in an actual work setting and assimilate their academic learning into practical applications</li>
	<li>Develop and instill among the students the industry-desired values of positive work attitude, good human relations, competency in technical skills that pertain to their fields of the study, and the openness to keep on learning to reinvent themselves.</li>
	<li>Enable the student to gain experience, relate and apply the theories and concepts they learned in school/classrooms to real industrial scenarios and problems</li>
	<li>Instill in the students the importance of human relations in the working environment.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>General Requirements for OJT:</strong></b>
</div>
<ol start="1">
	<li>All BSIT, BSCS, BSIS and ACT students who finished the required units prerequisite to the course must undergo Practicum/OJT (I and/or II), in partial fulfillment of the program.</li>
	<li>The minimum required number of hours of training per program should be in compliance with the guidelines mentioned in Section 11 of CMO No. 53, Series of 2006.</li>
	<li>A student is required to submit the following documents as part of the final report at the end of his/her training:
<ul>
	<li>Letter of Application with comprehensive resume/profile</li>
	<li>Letter of endorsement</li>
	<li>Letter of Acceptance/Approval from the company</li>
	<li>Parents/Guardianâ€™s Consent and/or Waiver</li>
	<li>Daily Attendance Report (DTR)</li>
	<li>Weekly Accomplishment/Progress Report</li>
	<li>Employer/Supervisor Evaluation Forms</li>
	<li>OJT/Practicum Experience Summary Report (in narrative form, overall, review and analysis of OJT experience)</li>
	<li>Photo Documentation of the actual training</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>Procedure for the Student Trainees:</strong></b>
</div>
<ol start="1">
	<li>The student trainee is required to attend the OJT orientation set by the college and submit the necessary documents:
<ul>
	<li>Comprehensive Resume</li>
	<li>2x2 ID Picture</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>The student should prepare the required documents addressed to the company concerned, endorsed by the OJT Coordinator/Adviser and the Head of the School of Computer Studies.</li>
	<li>The student is responsible for following up his/her application.</li>
	<li>Upon acceptance by the company, the student must inform the OJT coordinator by submitting any proof of his acceptance (Letter of Acceptance/Approval from the company).</li>
	<li>The student submits the waiver form, signed by the parent/s or guardian/s to the faculty coordinator.</li>
	<li>The student starts at the recommended date. He/She must record his/her daily attendance indicating the log-in/log-out time. The supervisor must sign it daily. The daily Attendance Record must be submitted to the practicum coordinator/adviser on a twice-a-month basis (cut-off period, 15th and 30th) and must be compiled attached in the OJT Experience Summary Report.</li>
	<li>The student is required to report to his/her practicum adviser once a week to discuss the problems and some queries.</li>
	<li>The student is required to make a progress report, on a day-to-day basis, which is to be submitted weekly to be practicum coordinator/adviser.</li>
	<li>The student should at all times keep all documents pertaining to his/her OJT.</li>
	<li>The student must comply with the general guidelines of the company regarding their own OJT program.</li>
	<li>The student is required to submit a hardbound of compilation of the accomplishment report as one of the final requirements.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>Duties and responsibilities of the Student trainees:</strong></b>
</div>
<ol start="1">
	<li>Each student trainee has the following responsibilities within the company:
<ul>
	<li>Data Encoding</li>
	<li>Conductor of IT-Related Research</li>
	<li>Technical Support</li>
	<li>Customer Service</li>
	<li>Program Development</li>
	<li>Office Works (answering phone calls, photocopying, record keeping)</li>
	<li>Familiarization in the functions/jobs done by the employees handing "Computer or IT Related" work in the firm.</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Student trainee must always observe discipline and right conduct in performing his/her task while on training.</li>
	<li>Student trainee must comply to OJT guidelines and procedures provided by the Practicum Coordinator/Adviser.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>Duties and Responsibilities of the Practicum Industry Partner</strong></b>
</div>
The Industry partner has the following duties and responsibilities:
<ol start="1">
	<li>Designates an Academic Supervisor or Training Coordinator who will ensure that OJT Program of the students is properly carried out at the facilities, plant or office of the Company.</li>
	<li>Ensures a safe working environment for students undergoing OJT.</li>
	<li>Ensures that all the documents needed by the trainees are complete before the start of the training.</li>
	<li>Upon completion of the required number of hours, the Training Coordinator shall issue a certificate of the completion to the trainees.</li>
	<li>The company shall not be bound to pay the on-the-job trainee any salary.</li>
	<li>The assigned supervisor shall fill out and sign the OJT Performance Evaluation Forms.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>Duties and Responsibilities of Practicum Coordinator/Adviser</strong></b>
</div>
<ol start="1">
	<li>Assists the Head in preparing and implementing the program of activities of the Practicum Program.</li>
	<li>Assists the Head in the selection of industry partners/practicum partners/venues.</li>
	<li>Assists the Head in the scheduling of practicum subjects.</li>
	<li>Helps in the proper implementation of the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) between the College and the practicum partner.</li>
	<li>Coordinates with the heads/managers of the practicum partners regarding the activities and needs/requirements of the student-trainees relative to the practicum program.</li>
	<li>Prepares the student trainees to their practicum/training through series of orientations, meetings, conferences and workshops.</li>
	<li>Confers with the student trainees to their practicum/training through series of orientations, meetings, conferences and workshops.</li>
	<li>Conducts regular observations and evaluation of the performance of the student-trainees.</li>
	<li>Assigns readings which might benefit the student trainees.</li>
	<li>Coordinates regularly with the practicum partners regarding the performance of the student-trainees.</li>
	<li>Serves as intermediary in situations that may arise with the practicum partners.</li>
	<li>Submits written report to the Dean, copy furnished the heads/managers regarding the status of the practicum program. (e.g. progress/performance of student-trainees; problems/difficulties met by the student-trainees; solution/actions taken to solve the concerns).</li>
	<li>Conducts exit interview/case studies if student-trainees.</li>
	<li>Rates/Evaluates the performance of the student-trainees based on the evaluation of heads/managers and the completion of all requirements as determined by the college.</li>
	<li>Maintains wholesome public relations with the practicum partners.</li>
	<li>Ensures close communication, getting all involved persons to give their best efforts in providing a successful learning experience for the student-trainees.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>Duties and responsibilities of the Parents/Guardian</strong></b>
</div>
<ol start="1">
	<li>To encourage the student to carry out effectively his/her duties and responsibilities.</li>
	<li>To share responsibilities for the conduct of the student while in the training program.</li>
	<li>To be responsible for the safety and conduct of the student-learner while travelling to and from the school, the OJT site and home.</li>
</ol>
<div>
<b><strong>General Information</strong></b>
<b><strong>Practicum Partner Evaluation</strong></b>
</div>
Each employer will be supplied with forms to analyze and grade each student. The employer has been asked to go over the evaluation with you. The Employer Rating Form must be filled out by the employer and returned by the student with manual and report.

IT IS THE STUDENTSâ€™ RESPONSIBILITY TO SUBMIT THIS FORM; THE CLASS ADVISER WILL NOT CONTACT EMPLOYERS ABOUT DELINQUENT FORMS.
<div>
<b><strong>Practicum Coordinator/Adviser Visits and Evaluations</strong></b>
</div>
During the OJT Period, practicum adviser will visit each student and will confer with his/her supervisor concerning the studentâ€™s performance and progress.
<div>
<b><strong>Practicum Coordinator/Adviser Visits and Evaluations</strong></b>
</div>
When all requirements have been submitted and reviewed, the grading system will be based on the following:
<div>
<b><strong>OJT Training Period</strong></b>
</div>
20% Â  Â  Weekly Progress Report

20% Â  Â  OJT Experience Summary Report

20% Â  Â  Practicum Adviser/Coordinator Evaluation

60% Â  Â  Practicum Partner Supervisor Evaluation
<div>
<b><strong>OJT Safety Requirements</strong></b>
</div>
With increased emphasis on worker safety, all students undergoing OJT should check with their employers for specific safety regulations.
<div>
<b><strong>IMPACT OF OJT</strong></b>
</div>
In addition to the college credit as required for graduation, OJT supplies a vital contact with industry and an additional interference for future job applications. Your effectiveness â€“ both on job performance and attitude â€“ will be piped into the industry grapevine and will provide you with either a good or bad industry reference.

Any student who commits to an OJT site must stay for the entire OJT period. Any exceptions to this policy must be approved in writing by the College Dean and/or Chair and their concerned immediate Supervisor. Failure to abide by this policy will result in the student in receiving a grade of FAILED.

Any student who quits, who is fired, or is â€œlet goâ€ for disciplinary reasons from the OT site will receive a FAILED Grade. A student cannot withdraw from OJT to avoid getting a grade of â€œFAILEDâ€. Any exceptions must be approved in writing by the College Dean and/or Chair.
<div>
<b><strong>OJT Site/Company Selection Process</strong></b>
</div>
OJT will be from ______________. You must work on this period in order to credit for OJT. You may work longer in order to earn more experience if you so desire. You are NOT to take vacations, etc., on your own. If any special problems occur, you must let the practicum adviser know and work out a solution before leaving for OJT.

Each student should select his/her own sit from an approved list of employers or by consulting with the practicum adviser. Good training rather than convenience should be a high priority in the selection process. Sites are to be within 5 miles from the school premises. Students desiring to go beyond the 5 mile area must justify their request to College Dean/Chair.

Students are to contact the prospective OJT employers in a professional manner. This is a good test of your professional conduct when seeking employment. Call the employer, state your name and reason for the call and set up an interview. There may be many students seeking the same site, so it will be â€œfirst come, first serveâ€. Make certain that you communicate clearly with all the employers you contact. You do not want to give an employer the impression that you are going to work at site â€œAâ€ when you have committed to work at Site â€œBâ€.
<div>
<b><strong>Eligibility for OJT;</strong></b>
</div>
Students who are enrolled in the college for their last semester before graduations are eligible for OJT. Students, who are not on the normal program schedule, must see the College Dean/Chair to determine their eligibility for OJT. You should select a site that will help you gain experience areas where you have little field training.

Any special request or problems must be handled through the College Dean/Chair.

<b><span style="text-decoration: underline;">ACADEMIC PARTNERSHIPS</span></b>

&nbsp;
<div>
<b><strong>BlackBerry Ltd.</strong></b>
</div>
BlackBerry Limited, formerly known as Research In Motion Limited (RIM),is a Canadian telecommunication and wireless equipment company best known as the developer of the BlackBerry brand of smartphones and tablets. The company is headquartered in Waterloo, Ontario, Canada. It was founded by Mike Lazaridis, who served as its co-CEO along with Jim Balsillie until January 22, 2012; as of August 2013, the company\'s CEO is Thorsten Heins.

